Comparing Burnesâ€™ Pitching Performance: A Deep Dive into 2018-2019 vs 2020-2024

Research Question

Corbin Burnes transformed his pitching repertoire by using cutter instead of 4-seam fastball in 2020, a decision that significantly impacted his performance. My research investigates the changes in Burnesâ€™ pitching stats before and after this transition, focusing on key metrics such as Earned Run Average (ERA), FIP, WHIP, and Walks per Nine Innings (BB9). By examining how his pitch repertoire evolved and its effect on his overall performance, this analysis aims to highlight the effectiveness of introducing the cutter into his arsenal, showing the proof that one pitcherâ€™s career could be changed dramatically due to the addition of one suitable pitch.

Narrative Text

Reason why I want to investigate this topic: The primary motivation behind analyzing Corbin Burnesâ€™ pitching transformation is to understand how a single pitchâ€”the cutterâ€”can redefine a playerâ€™s career. Burnesâ€™ performance in 2018-2019 was disappointing, but his reinvention as a pitcher in 2020-2024 showcases the profound impact of adapting and evolving in professional sports. By diving into his statistical changes, I hope to uncover the specific ways the cutter improved his overall effectiveness and contributed to his dominance.

One significant technical challenge: One of the most significant challenges in this project was ensuring the accuracy and consistency of the data. Burnesâ€™ pitching stats were split across two distinct time periods: 2018-2019 and 2020-2024. Merging these datasets while maintaining the integrity of key metrics required careful cleaning and validation. Additionally, selecting relevant metrics to evaluate his performanceâ€”while avoiding information overloadâ€”demanded thoughtful consideration and data manipulation.

Significant findings or conclusions: This detailed analysis of Corbin Burnesâ€™ transformation from his pre-cutter (2018-2019) to post-cutter (2020-2024) seasons highlights several key areas of improvement following the introduction of the cutter:

  1. Pitch Mix Evolution: In the pre-cutter period, Burnes predominantly relied on a two-pitch mix of the 4-seam fastball (54.3%) and slider (31.9%). However, from 2020 onwards, Burnes replaced the 4-seam fastball with the cutter, which became his primary pitch (50.5%). This shift allowed Burnes to incorporate a more varied pitch repertoire, including an increased use of breaking balls such as the curveball, changeup, and sinker, which complemented his cutter effectively.

  2. Improved Performance Metrics: Batting Average (BA): Burnes saw a notable decrease in opponentsâ€™ batting averages across nearly all pitches after adding the cutter. The changeup and curveball, in particular, showed marked improvements, with batting averages against them significantly lower in the post-cutter seasons.

Slugging Percentage (SLG): Similar to BA, opponentsâ€™ slugging percentages against Burnesâ€™ pitches also dropped after the cutter was incorporated, particularly on pitches like the changeup and curveball. This highlights Burnesâ€™ improved ability to limit hard contact and extra-base hits after 2020.

Whiffs: The cutter became Burnesâ€™ most effective pitch for generating whiffs, significantly boosting his strikeout potential. Even with the reduction in slider usage (from 32% to 9%), Burnes generated more whiffs on the slider in the post-cutter seasons, reflecting an overall improvement in his ability to miss bats. Walks and Control: The addition of the cutter not only improved Burnesâ€™ strikeout potential but also enhanced his control, as evidenced by the decrease in walks per nine innings (BB/9). This resulted in fewer free passes and a more efficient pitching approach.

  1. Overall Pitching Effectiveness: Burnesâ€™ transformation into an elite pitcher can be attributed to the incorporation of the cutter, which allowed him to improve across multiple metrics, including ERA, FIP, HR/9, K/9, and WHIP. His pitch mix diversification and increased reliance on the cutter helped him become a more unpredictable and dominant force on the mound.

Conclusion: Corbin Burnesâ€™ adoption of the cutter marked a pivotal turning point in his pitching career, significantly enhancing his performance and transforming him into one of the top starting pitchers in Major League Baseball. The cutter not only improved key metrics such as BA, SLG, and K/9 but also facilitated a more diverse and effective pitch selection. Burnesâ€™ evolution exemplifies the importance of adaptability and innovation in professional baseball, demonstrating how the continuous refinement of oneâ€™s pitch mix can lead to sustained success and dominance on the mound.

KEY Stats in this Project ERA (Earned Run Average) A widely-used metric that measures a pitcherâ€™s ability to prevent earned runs. It reflects the overall effectiveness in managing opposing offenses.

BB/9 (Walks per Nine Innings) This stat highlights a pitcherâ€™s control by showing how many walks they allow per nine innings. Lowering BB/9 indicates better command and fewer free passes to batters.

FIP (Fielding Independent Pitching) FIP isolates a pitcherâ€™s performance by focusing on factors under their controlâ€”strikeouts, walks, and home runsâ€”while removing fielding influence. It gives a clearer picture of Burnesâ€™ pitching skills.

WHIP (Walks + Hits per Inning Pitched) A key metric for assessing how effectively a pitcher prevents batters from reaching base. WHIP combines walks and hits, providing an overview of a pitcherâ€™s ability to limit base runners.

Pitching Effectiveness HR/9 (Home Runs per Nine Innings) HR/9 measures a pitcherâ€™s ability to prevent home runs, which limits extra-base hits and runs. Comparing pre- and post-cutter HR/9 gives insight into whether Burnes improved at limiting long balls after adding the cutter.

K/9 (Strikeouts per Nine Innings) K/9 tracks a pitcherâ€™s strikeout rate. After adding the cutter, K/9 can show how the pitch contributed to Burnesâ€™ ability to generate strikeouts.

Control and Command BA (Batting Average Against) BA Against measures how successful batters are at making contact with the pitcherâ€™s pitches. A decrease in BA after adding the cutter signals improved pitching performance.

SLG (Slugging Percentage Against) SLG shows how many extra-base hits batters are able to produce. A lower SLG indicates that Burnes improved at limiting hard contact and extra-base hits after incorporating the cutter.

Strikeouts and Contact Whiffs (Swinging Strikes) Tracks how often batters swing and miss at Burnesâ€™ pitches. An increase in whiffs suggests that his pitches, particularly the cutter, are generating more swings and misses.

Other Metrics BK (Balks): A pitcherâ€™s illegal motion that allows runners to advance.

BF (Batters Faced): Total number of batters a pitcher faces during an outing.

WP (Wild Pitches): The number of pitches the catcher cannot handle, allowing runners to advance.

This code adds a new period column to each dataset to distinguish between the 2018-2019 (pre-cutter) and 2020-2024 (post-cutter) periods. The datasets are then merged with bind_rows() into a single dataset for analysis. Finally, the column names of the combined dataset are checked to ensure consistency and clarity.

# Calculate averages for each metric within each period
combined_data_avg <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(period) %>%
  summarise(
    ERA = mean(ERA, na.rm = TRUE),
    K9 = mean(SO.9, na.rm = TRUE),
    BB9 = mean(BB.9, na.rm = TRUE),
    FIP = mean(FIP, na.rm = TRUE),
    WHIP = mean(WHIP, na.rm = TRUE),
    HR9 = mean(HR.9, na.rm = TRUE),
    )

# Check the calculated averages

The average values for key pitching metrics (ERA, K/9, BB/9, FIP, WHIP, HR/9) were calculated for each period (2018-2019 and 2020-2024). The group_by() function was used to separate the data by period, and then summarise() was applied to compute the mean for each metric. Afterward, glimpse() was used to review the results and ensure accuracy.

This code adds period and pitch type labels to each dataset, indicating whether the data is from the 2018-2019 or 2020-2024 period and specifying which pitch type (e.g., Fastball, Sinker, Cutter, etc.) each row of data corresponds to. After labeling, the datasets for each pitch type and period are combined into one unified dataset using bind_rows(). The resulting Burnes_pitch_data allows for pitch-specific analysis over the two periods. Finally, glimpse() is used to inspect the structure of the combined dataset and ensure it has been successfully merged.

Burnes_pitch_repertoire <- Burnes_pitch_data %>%
  mutate(usage_percentage = case_when(
    period == "2018-2019" & pitch_type == "Fastball" ~ 54.3,
    period == "2018-2019" & pitch_type == "Sinker" ~ 2.3,
    period == "2018-2019" & pitch_type == "Cutter" ~ 0.7,
    period == "2018-2019" & pitch_type == "Changeup" ~ 2.4,
    period == "2018-2019" & pitch_type == "Curve" ~ 7.3,
    period == "2018-2019" & pitch_type == "Slider" ~ 31.9,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Fastball" ~ 0.6,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Sinker" ~ 9.8,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Cutter" ~ 50.5,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Changeup" ~ 10.5,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Curve" ~ 18.1,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Slider" ~ 9.0,
    period == "2020-2024" & pitch_type == "Sweeper" ~ 1.5,
    TRUE ~ NA_real_
  ))

This code adds a new column, usage_percentage, to the Burnes_pitch_data dataset, representing the usage percentage of each pitch type for Burnes during the 2018-2019 and 2020-2024 periods. The case_when() function assigns specific percentages based on the pitch type and period. The resulting Burnes_pitch_repertoire dataset includes this additional information, making it ready for further analysis.

Given the huge difference in Corbin Burnesâ€™ pitching repertoire between the pre-cutter and post-cutter seasons, I analyzed the pitching metrics for each of his pitches to understand how the shift in repertoire influenced his performance.

Burnes_pitch_performance <- Burnes_pitch_repertoire %>%
  group_by(period, pitch_type) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_BB9 = mean(bb_percent, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_ba = mean(ba, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_slg = mean(slg, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_spinrate = mean(spin_rate, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_whiffs = mean(whiffs, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'period'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Filter only the desired metrics (avg_ba, avg_slg, avg_whiffs)
metrics_of_interest <- c("avg_ba", "avg_slg", "avg_whiffs")

Burnes_pitch_performance_long <- Burnes_pitch_performance %>%
  gather(key = "metric", value = "value", avg_BB9:avg_whiffs) %>%
  filter(metric %in% metrics_of_interest)  # Filter for the selected metrics

This code calculates and reshapes pitching performance data for Burnes, focusing on three key metrics: batting average (BA), slugging percentage (SLG), and whiff rate. It computes the average values for these metrics by pitch type and period, then reshapes the data into a long format for easier comparison across the two periods (2018-2019 and 2020-2024).

# Plot 1: Batting Average (avg_ba)
ggplot(Burnes_pitch_performance_long %>% filter(metric == "avg_ba"), aes(x = pitch_type, y = value, color = period, group = period)) +
  geom_line() +  
  geom_point() + 
  labs(
    title = "Batting Average by Pitch Type and Period",
    x = "Pitch Type",
    y = "Average BA",
    color = "Period"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

This line graph shows the batting average of hitters faced by Corbin Burnes during the pre-cutter (2018-2019) and post-cutter (2020-2024) seasons. In the pre-cutter seasons, Burnesâ€™ changeup and curveball were hit hard, with batting averages over .300 on the changeup and over .500 on the curveball. As the graph illustrates, almost every pitch Burnes used during his pre-cutter seasons had a higher batting average than in the post-cutter seasons, except for his fastball and sinker. The batting average against his sinker remained nearly identical, while the average against his fastball slightly decreased, but still remained above .300 in both periods.

In contrast, every pitch in Burnesâ€™ 2020-2024 repertoire showed a lower batting average compared to the pre-cutter seasons, except for the fastball, which he used much less. Notably, hittersâ€™ batting averages against Burnesâ€™ changeup and curveball significantly dropped after he added the cutter to his repertoire. This illustrates how incorporating the cutter helped improve Burnesâ€™ performance and contributed to his career success.

In the post-cutter seasons, Burnes effectively utilized his pitch repertoire, significantly lowering hittersâ€™ slugging percentages, especially on the changeup, curveball, and sinker â€” pitches he relied on much more in 2020-2024. The slugging percentage against his cutter was nearly identical in both periods, but since the cutterâ€™s usage increased dramatically in the post-cutter seasons, it demonstrates that Burnes adapted and used his pitches more effectively.

This visualization shows the whiffs of hitters faced by Corbin Burnes during the pre-cutter (2018-2019) and post-cutter (2020-2024) seasons.

In the pre-cutter seasons, Burnes generated very few whiffs on his changeup, curveball, and sinker. Most of his whiffs came from the fastball and slider, which were the two pitches he relied on the most.

However, from 2020-2024, after Burnes incorporated the cutter into his arsenal and used it more than 50% of the time, he saw a significant increase in whiffs. The cutter became his most effective pitch for generating whiffs. Additionally, he recorded many more whiffs on his changeup, curveball, slider, and sinker.

Itâ€™s important to note the whiffs against the slider. Despite using the slider less (dropping from 32% usage to 9%), Burnes still generated 151 more whiffs on it in the post-cutter seasons compared to the pre-cutter seasons.

This line graph demonstrates that Burnes became a much more effective all-around pitcher by adding the cutter to his repertoire, replacing the 4-seam fastball with the cutter, and adjusting his pitch mix by reducing slider usage and increasing reliance on other breaking balls, such as the changeup, curveball, and sinker.
